		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">While the quantum theoretical modelling of chemical reactions at surfaces has made enormous progress recently, the theory of active manipulation of adsorbates at surfaces with scanning tunnelling microscopes (STMs), or lasers, is still lagging behind. As a contribution to fill this gap, we propose to use input from first principles electronic structure theory for nuclear quantum dynamical calculations which cover characteristic aspects of STM- and laser-induced processes, such as desorption, lateral, and reversible vertical motion.  Specifically, we wish to explain a strong temperature effect for the STM-desorption of H atoms from a Si (100) surface, and develop an theoretical framework for these processes which is free of fargoing model assumptions.  Theses more general methods will then be used to study the possibility of an  atomic switch  consisting of an atom (H), which is bound chemically to a metal surface (Cu), and jumps reversibly back and forth between the surface and a STM tip, possibly undergoing also lateral motion.  The relative importance of different reaction channels and the extent to which they can be actively controlled, will be exploited.  Finally, pure electric field effects will be studied for STM- an infrared laser induced desorption and adsorption of H3 molecules at copper.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
